    "body": "## Description\r\n\r\nCloses #3135.\r\n\r\nThis PR enables using struct-like types as algorithm inputs.\r\n\r\n### Example\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n  <summary>Click to see example</summary>\r\n\r\nBelow, we define a custom type called `Pixel` (composed of RGB values), and perform a reduction on an array of `Pixel` objects to find the one with the largest `g` component:\r\n\r\n```python\r\n\r\nfrom cuda.parallel.experimental.algorithms import reduce_into\r\nfrom cuda.parallel.experimental.struct import gpu_struct\r\n\r\nimport numpy as np, cupy as cp\r\n\r\n# define a struct type:\r\n@gpu_struct\r\nclass Pixel:\r\n    r: np.int32\r\n    g: np.int32\r\n    b: np.int32\r\n\r\n# binary op that operates on our custom type:\r\ndef max_g_value(x, y):\r\n    return x if x.g > y.g else y\r\n\r\n# initialize input, output and initial data:\r\nd_rgb = cp.random.randint(0, 256, (10, 3), dtype=np.int32).view(Pixel.dtype)\r\nd_out = cp.zeros(1, Pixel.dtype)\r\nh_init = Pixel(0, 0, 0)\r\n\r\n# create reducer object:\r\nreducer = reduce_into(d_rgb, d_out, max_g_value, h_init)\r\n\r\n# compute and allocate temp storage:\r\ntemp_storage_bytes = reducer(None, d_rgb, d_out, len(d_rgb), h_init)\r\nd_temp_storage = cp.zeros(temp_storage_bytes, dtype=np.uint8)\r\n\r\n# perform reduction:\r\n_ = reducer(d_temp_storage, d_rgb, d_out, len(d_rgb), h_init)\r\n\r\n# # # results:\r\nprint()\r\nprint(\"Input RGB values:\")\r\nprint(\"-----------------\")\r\nprint(d_rgb.get())\r\nprint()\r\nprint(\"Value with largest g component:\")\r\nprint(\"-------------------------------\")\r\nprint(d_out.get())\r\nprint()\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\n# output:\r\nInput RGB values:\r\n-----------------\r\n[[(148,  54,  81)]\r\n [( 22, 249, 159)]\r\n [(115, 206,  87)]\r\n [(156, 190, 239)]\r\n [( 99, 191,   7)]\r\n [(232, 169,  46)]\r\n [( 41,  90, 230)]\r\n [(214, 134, 202)]\r\n [( 50,  80, 129)]\r\n [(169, 169,  12)]]\r\n\r\nValue with largest g component:\r\n-------------------------------\r\n[(22, 249, 159)]\r\n```\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n\r\n### Implementation\r\n\r\nThe primary addition in this PR is the decorator `@gpu_struct`. It's a user-facing decorator, which enables them to define a struct similar to a dataclass. Under the hood, `@gpu_struct` makes a numba type corresponding to the struct, and enables  it to be used in device functions (such as user defined binary and unary operations). As far as the CCCL C library is concerned, instances of this type are treated as `STORAGE_T`.\r\n\r\n⚠️ This PR supports \"flat\" (non-nested) struct dtypes. I _think_ it should be possible to add support for nested structs, but would prefer to do that in a future PR.\r\n\r\n#### Why not use structured dtypes?\r\n\r\nInstead of having the user define a custom dataclass-like struct type, we could have them pass numpy [structured dtypes instead](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/user/basics.rec.html#structured-datatypes). However, this was rejected. The primary reason is that for Python functions accepting/returning structured dtypes, numba generates device functions accepting/returning _pointers_ to structs. This is problematic for two reasons: (1) In the context of CCCL, binary/unary ops are expected to take arguments of type `T` rather than `T*`, and (2) memory management - who will keep the `T*` returned by the binary operation of a reduction alive?\r\n\r\nConsider the following device function:\r\n\r\n```python\r\ndef max_g_value(x, y):\r\n    return x if x['g'] > y['g'] else y\r\n```\r\n\r\nBelow are the PTX generated by numba after compiling the function for (1) inputs as raw struct dtypes, (2) inputs as \"wrapper\" types. Note that for raw structs, the PTX code expects pointer-to-structs as input:\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n<summary> Raw struct input PTX </summary>\r\n\r\n```ptx\r\n//\r\n// Generated by NVIDIA NVVM Compiler\r\n//\r\n// Compiler Build ID: CL-35059454\r\n// Cuda compilation tools, release 12.6, V12.6.85\r\n// Based on NVVM 7.0.1\r\n//\r\n\r\n.version 8.5\r\n.target sm_50\r\n.address_size 64\r\n\r\n        // .globl       max_g_value\r\n.common .global .align 8 .u64 _ZN08NumbaEnv8__main__11max_g_valueB2v1B92cw51cXTLSUwv1sDUaKthqqNgoKmjgOR3W3CwAkMXLaJtQYkOIgxJU0gCqOkEJoHkbttqdVhoqlspQGNFHSgJ5BnXagIAE6RecordILi598EE6RecordILi598EE;\r\n.visible .func  (.param .b64 func_retval0) max_g_value(\r\n        .param .b64 max_g_value_param_0,\r\n        .param .b64 max_g_value_param_1\r\n)\r\n{\r\n        .reg .pred      %p<2>;\r\n        .reg .b32       %r<3>;\r\n        .reg .b64       %rd<4>;\r\n\r\n\r\n        ld.param.u64    %rd1, [max_g_value_param_0];\r\n        ld.param.u64    %rd2, [max_g_value_param_1];\r\n        ld.u32  %r1, [%rd1+4];\r\n        ld.u32  %r2, [%rd2+4];\r\n        setp.gt.s32     %p1, %r1, %r2;\r\n        selp.b64        %rd3, %rd1, %rd2, %p1;\r\n        st.param.b64    [func_retval0+0], %rd3;\r\n        ret;\r\n\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n<summary> Wrapper type input </summary>\r\n\r\n```ptx\r\n//\r\n// Generated by NVIDIA NVVM Compiler\r\n//\r\n// Compiler Build ID: CL-35059454\r\n// Cuda compilation tools, release 12.6, V12.6.85\r\n// Based on NVVM 7.0.1\r\n//\r\n\r\n.version 8.5\r\n.target sm_50\r\n.address_size 64\r\n\r\n        // .globl       max_g_value\r\n.common .global .align 8 .u64 _ZN08NumbaEnv8__main__11max_g_valueB2v1B92cw51cXTLSUwv1sDUaKthqqNgoKmjgOR3W3CwAkMXLaJtQYkOIgxJU0gCqOkEJoHkbttqdVhoqlspQGNFHSgJ5BnXagIAE13StructWrapper13StructWrapper;\r\n\r\n.visible .func  (.param .align 4 .b8 func_retval0[12]) max_g_value(\r\n        .param .b32 max_g_value_param_0,\r\n        .param .b32 max_g_value_param_1,\r\n        .param .b32 max_g_value_param_2,\r\n        .param .b32 max_g_value_param_3,\r\n        .param .b32 max_g_value_param_4,\r\n        .param .b32 max_g_value_param_5\r\n)\r\n{\r\n        .reg .pred      %p<2>;\r\n        .reg .b32       %r<10>;\r\n\r\n\r\n        ld.param.u32    %r1, [max_g_value_param_0];\r\n        ld.param.u32    %r2, [max_g_value_param_1];\r\n        ld.param.u32    %r3, [max_g_value_param_2];\r\n        ld.param.u32    %r4, [max_g_value_param_3];\r\n        ld.param.u32    %r5, [max_g_value_param_4];\r\n        ld.param.u32    %r6, [max_g_value_param_5];\r\n        setp.gt.s32     %p1, %r2, %r5;\r\n        selp.b32        %r7, %r3, %r6, %p1;\r\n        max.s32         %r8, %r2, %r5;\r\n        selp.b32        %r9, %r1, %r4, %p1;\r\n        st.param.b32    [func_retval0+0], %r9;\r\n        st.param.b32    [func_retval0+4], %r8;\r\n        st.param.b32    [func_retval0+8], %r7;\r\n        ret;\r\n\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n(for posterity, the PTX generated can be viewed by compiling the code for output type `\"ptx\"` in [this function](https://github.com/NVIDIA/cccl/blob/7fab84dce3860c2f3a8dc67bd4e51db3ebf7ea97/python/cuda_parallel/cuda/parallel/experimental/algorithms/reduce.py#L19-L26) and running the unit test introduced in this PR).\r\n\r\n### Note to reviewers\r\n\r\nThe API here is a little awkward, and I definitely invite suggestions for improvement. However, we may want to consider iterating on the API/implementation in follow-up PRs. In an offline discussion with @gevtushenko, we discussed that as a first pass, it's sufficient that we have _some_ way to work with structs from Python so that the corresponding C codepath is tested. \r\n\r\n## Checklist\r\n<!-- TODO: - [x] I am familiar with the [Contributing Guidelines](). -->\r\n- [x] New or existing tests cover these changes.\r\n- [x] The documentation is up to date with these changes.\r\n",
